1. We have that |$\overrightarrow{a}| = 1$ and |$\overrightarrow{b}| = 2$, so by the triangle inequality we have:
$$|\overrightarrow{a} + \overrightarrow{b}| \leq |\overrightarrow{a}| + |\overrightarrow{b}| = 1 + 2 = \boxed{3}$$
The equality holds in this case, since $\overrightarrow{a}$ and $\overrightarrow{b}$ have zero scalar product.

2. We want to find the cosine of the angle $\theta$ between $\overrightarrow{a}$ and $\overrightarrow{b} - \overrightarrow{a}$. We have:
\begin{align*}
\cos \theta &= \frac{\overrightarrow{a} \cdot (\overrightarrow{b} - \overrightarrow{a})}{|\overrightarrow{a}| \cdot |\overrightarrow{b} - \overrightarrow{a}|} \\
&= \frac{-\frac{1}{2} - \overrightarrow{a} \cdot \overrightarrow{a}}{\sqrt{1 \cdot (\overrightarrow{b} - \overrightarrow{a})^2}} \\
&= \frac{-\frac{3}{2}}{\sqrt{(\overrightarrow{b} - \overrightarrow{a})^2}} = \boxed{-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}
\end{align*}

